<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="68" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,152,642]" pageId="6" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,318,461,487]" pageId="6" pageNumber="68">Remarks.</emphasis>
We found specimens of this species on days with good sunshine; most of these specimens were collected while they were visiting railway beggarticks (
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus" authorityName="Linnaeus" box="[829,1117,500,526]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Bidens" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="6" pageNumber="68" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis box="[829,994,500,525]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="68">Bidens pilosa</emphasis>
Linnaeus
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName box="[1130,1265,500,526]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="6" pageNumber="68" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
) (Fig. 
<number box="[1348,1362,500,526]" pageId="6" pageNumber="68" value="1.0">1</number>
). The species flies slower than other genera of bee flies. The environment in which we found this species is similar to that where locusts oviposit, so future collecting of this species in 
<collectingCountry box="[949,1019,577,603]" name="China" pageId="6" pageNumber="68">China</collectingCountry>
and elsewhere should also look for possible parasitoid associations between this species and locusts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
